3. Proposed Mitigation Strategy: Rate Limiting

The primary recommendation to prevent future occurrences is the implementation of Rate Limiting at the Nginx reverse proxy level.

Rate limiting allows the server to define a "safety ceiling" for the number of requests any single IP address can make in a given timeframe (e.g., 10 requests per second). When an attacker exceeds this limit, the server automatically drops their additional requests, protecting the backend resources.
4. Justification for the Proposed Solution

Rate limiting is the industry-standard defense for this scenario for several reasons:

    Resource Fairness: It ensures that one malicious actor cannot "starve" legitimate users of server resources.

    Low Latency: Unlike deep packet inspection, rate limiting at the proxy level is computationally "cheap" and does not slow down legitimate traffic.

    Automated Defense: Once configured, it requires no manual intervention to block automated scripts like the one identified in this incident.

5. Steps for Implementation

To implement this on our Nginx servers, the following steps are required:

    Define the Limit Zone: Add a limit_req_zone in the http block of the Nginx configuration to track IP addresses.

    Apply to Location: Add the limit_req directive to the specific location / block.

    Configure Bursting: Set a "burst" parameter to allow for small, legitimate spikes in traffic (e.g., page refreshes) without blocking the user.

    Test Configuration: Run nginx -t to ensure syntax validity before reloading the service.

6. Post-Implementation Monitoring

To ensure the solution is effective and does not impact legitimate users, we will implement:

    Log Monitoring: Use grep or awk scripts to monitor Nginx error logs for "429 Too Many Requests" statuses, which indicate the rate limiter is working.

    Visualization: Integrate Grafana or a similar dashboard to visualize the ratio of successful requests vs. rate-limited requests.

    Alerting: Set up automated alerts to trigger if a single IP address remains rate-limited for more than 10 consecutive minutes.

7. Conclusion

The analyzed incident was a textbook automated DoS attack. While the impact was temporary, it highlighted a lack of request throttling in our current configuration. By implementing the proposed rate-limiting strategy, we significantly harden the application against automated scripts and ensure high availability for our actual users.
